## Obtaining the source code
1. Install Git on your computer. 
   Here is a tutorial teaching how to install Git: 
   https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/install-git

2. Clone the repository with a command:
   $ git clone https://github.com/kulwadeesom/csc209_256002

3. To get new sample programs, use the following command:
   $ git pull  

4. Enjoy!

See: https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/learn-git-with-bitbucket-cloud 
for a Git tutorial.

## Building Programs
You are encouraged to use Java IDE (such as Eclipse, NetBeans, and IntelliJ IDEA) 
to develop and build your programs. 

Even so, I have found that it is sometimes more convenient to use a plain 
text-based editor (e.g. vi, Emacs) to work on my program. 

In the case that you are, like me, happy with using text-based interface.
I have prepared an Ant build file for you (build.xml). 

Here is how to use Ant I use Ant to build sample programs.
1. Clean the project workspace
$ ant clean

2. Build all programs
$ ant build

3. Run a program
$ ant <PROGRAM_TARGET_NAME>

Note that, you have to replace <PROGRAM_TARGET_NAME> with the target name of the 
sample program that you would like to execute. For example, to execute the 
StringClient1 sample program of lecture #1, just type:

$ ant lect01.StringClient1

